Nonfiction provides companion interviews that offer insight into the inspiration, drafting, and revision process that produced the essays. Cheryl Strayed talks about how working as a reporter for her hometown newspaper influenced her later writings. Dinty W. Moore reflects on the delicate balance between observation and judgment when writing about subjects whose values differ from your own. Kristen Radtke explains how she decides between textual and visual images when creating a graphic essay. Although they offer an eclectic mix of voices and styles, what these essays all have in common is that ultimately, as contributor Faith Adiele observes, "truth becomes art."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican essaysx21st century. 0aAmerican essaysy21st century. 0aAuthorsvInterviews. 0aAuthorsxInterviewsxInterviews. 0aCreative nonfiction. 0aReportage literature, American. 4aGeneral Interest : Autobigraphy. 4aGeneral Interest : Memoir. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / Nonfiction (incl. Memoirs).2bisacsh1 aAdiele, Faith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldrich, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorich, Barrie Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Fleda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurch, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConaway, Cameron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGermain, Sheryl St., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroom, Kelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r